1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,720
Hello English learners, welcome back to EnglishPod.
各位英语学习者，欢迎回到EnglishPod。

2
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:06,720
My name is Marco.
我是Marco。

3
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:07,840
And I'm Erica.
我是Erica。

4
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:14,000
And today we are going back in time again and this time we're going to be in the 1960s.
今天我们要再次穿越时空，这次我们要回到20世纪60年代。

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:15,000
That's right.
没错。

6
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,760
We're going to learn some phrases and some slang that were really popular back in 1964.
我们要学习一些在1964年非常流行的短语和俚语。

7
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:23,480
Exactly.
正是。

8
00:00:23,480 --> 00:00:26,920
And most of these phrases and words we still use today.
而且这些短语和词汇大部分我们今天还在用。

9
00:00:26,920 --> 00:00:29,520
So it's very interesting and very good to know.
所以这很有趣，也很值得了解。

10
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:30,520
That's right.
没错。

11
00:00:30,520 --> 00:00:33,280
I'm looking forward to this trip back in time.
我很期待这次时光之旅。

12
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:36,280
So why don't we get started with the dialogue.
那我们开始对话吧。

13
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:46,520
Hey man, I really like your pad.
嘿，老兄，我真的很喜欢你的公寓。

14
00:00:46,520 --> 00:00:48,640
Those lava lamps are far out.
那些熔岩灯太酷了。

15
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:50,520
Thanks for letting me crash here tonight.
谢谢你今晚让我借宿。

16
00:00:50,520 --> 00:00:52,200
It's no problem, brother.
没问题，兄弟。

17
00:00:52,200 --> 00:00:56,600
I wanted a pad where people could come, listen to music and just hang loose.
我想要一个地方，人们可以来听音乐，放松自在。

18
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:57,640
You dig what I'm saying?
你明白我的意思吗？

19
00:00:57,640 --> 00:00:58,640
I dig it, man.
我明白，老兄。

20
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:02,440
We should throw a bash here and make it a really happening scene.
我们应该在这儿办个派对，让它成为一个热闹的场面。

21
00:01:02,440 --> 00:01:03,880
Yeah, man.
是啊，老兄。

22
00:01:03,880 --> 00:01:04,880
That would be groovy.
那会很棒的。

23
00:01:04,880 --> 00:01:07,320
Hey, I got to split for a while.
嘿，我得离开一会儿。

24
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:09,080
Are you okay here by yourself?
你一个人在这儿没问题吧？

25
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:10,320
Don't worry about me, brother.
别担心我，兄弟。

26
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:12,480
You go take care of your business.
你去忙你的事吧。

27
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:13,480
All right.
好的。

28
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:14,480
Peace out.
再见。

29
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:15,480
All right.
好的。

30
00:01:15,480 --> 00:01:20,500
So great dialogue.
很棒的对话。

31
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:21,800
Very popular in the 60s.
在60年代非常流行。

32
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:25,040
The music, the mood and the words, right?
音乐、氛围和用词，对吧？

33
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:26,040
That's right.
没错。

34
00:01:26,040 --> 00:01:29,760
So why don't we get down to business and look at the vocabulary that we saw in this dialogue
那我们不如进入正题，看看对话中出现的词汇。

35
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:33,080
in Language Takeaway.
在“语言要点”部分。

36
00:01:33,080 --> 00:01:34,080
Language Takeaway.
语言要点。

37
00:01:34,080 --> 00:01:40,680
Well, the dialogue opened and we heard this guy say, hey man, I really like your pad.
对话一开始，我们听到这个人说：“嘿，老兄，我真的很喜欢你的公寓。”

38
00:01:40,680 --> 00:01:42,640
I really like your pad.
我真的很喜欢你的公寓。

39
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:43,640
Pad.
公寓。

40
00:01:43,640 --> 00:01:44,640
Okay.
好的。

41
00:01:44,640 --> 00:01:49,960
So pad, a very informal way of saying your apartment, your apartment, right?
所以“pad”是一种非常非正式的说法，指你的公寓，对吧？

42
00:01:49,960 --> 00:01:51,920
And now you can still use it today.
而且现在你仍然可以用它。

43
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:52,920
Yeah, that's right.
是的，没错。

44
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:56,080
We often hear the expression bachelor pad.
我们经常听到“bachelor pad”这个说法。

45
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:57,080
Okay.
好的。

46
00:01:57,080 --> 00:01:58,080
A bachelor pad.
单身公寓。

47
00:01:58,080 --> 00:02:00,280
So that's an apartment where a single man lives.
那是指单身男人住的公寓。

48
00:02:00,280 --> 00:02:01,280
Okay.
好的。

49
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:02,880
So a bachelor pad.
所以是单身公寓。

50
00:02:02,880 --> 00:02:07,720
Usually it's very nicely decorated and really a nice apartment, right?
通常装修得很好，是个很不错的公寓，对吧？

51
00:02:07,720 --> 00:02:11,720
Or maybe it has empty pizza boxes all over the floor, Marco.
或者可能地板上到处都是空披萨盒，Marco。

52
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:13,400
Also a bachelor pad.
那也是单身公寓。

53
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:15,960
But so that's what pad means, an apartment.
但这就是“pad”的意思，公寓。

54
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:16,960
Yeah.
是的。

55
00:02:16,960 --> 00:02:21,240
They were talking about the apartment and he said the lava lamps are far out.
他们在谈论公寓，他说熔岩灯太酷了。

56
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:22,240
Far out.
太酷了。

57
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:23,240
Okay.
好的。

58
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:24,560
It's far out.
太酷了。

59
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:27,920
So that's really cool or amazing.
那意思是真的很酷或很棒。

60
00:02:27,920 --> 00:02:28,920
Right.
对。

61
00:02:28,920 --> 00:02:33,960
And now lava lamps, those are those strange cone looking lamps, right?
现在熔岩灯，就是那些奇怪的锥形灯，对吧？

62
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:36,560
Kind of a light with like some liquid moving inside.
一种里面有液体流动的灯。

63
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:37,560
Moving inside.
里面流动。

64
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:38,560
Very popular in the 60s.
在60年代非常流行。

65
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:39,560
Yeah.
是的。

66
00:02:39,560 --> 00:02:40,560
We'll post some pictures of that.
我们会贴一些图片。

67
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:41,560
Yeah.
是的。

68
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:42,560
And the lamps are far out.
这些灯太酷了。

69
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:44,160
So now you can use that with other things, right?
所以你现在可以用它来形容其他东西，对吧？

70
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:45,480
Like you are really far out.
比如你真的很酷。

71
00:02:45,480 --> 00:02:46,480
Yeah.
是的。

72
00:02:46,480 --> 00:02:47,720
Or this music is really far out.
或者这音乐真的很酷。

73
00:02:47,720 --> 00:02:48,720
Okay.
好的。

74
00:02:48,720 --> 00:02:51,520
It kind of gives you the feeling like it's sort of spacey.
它给人一种有点迷幻的感觉。

75
00:02:51,520 --> 00:02:52,520
Yeah.
是的。

76
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:53,880
All right.
好的。

77
00:02:53,880 --> 00:02:55,520
So the pad is really far out.
所以这个公寓真的很酷。

78
00:02:55,520 --> 00:02:57,120
The lava lamps are great.
熔岩灯很棒。

79
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:01,320
And he was saying, thanks for letting me crash here tonight.
他说：“谢谢你今晚让我借宿。”

80
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:02,580
To crash.
借宿。

81
00:03:02,580 --> 00:03:05,080
So to crash at someone's place.
所以是在某人家里借宿。

82
00:03:05,080 --> 00:03:06,080
Right.
对。

83
00:03:06,080 --> 00:03:08,880
So we're not talking about like a car crash here.
我们这里说的不是车祸。

84
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:09,880
No, no, no.
不，不，不。

85
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:12,280
But so when you crash somewhere, what do you do?
但当你“crash”在某个地方时，你做什么？

86
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:14,040
Well, you are staying there.
嗯，你待在那里。

87
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:15,400
Then you're going to stay there.
你会待在那里。

88
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:16,400
So you're going to...
所以你会……

89
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:17,400
As a guest.
作为客人。

90
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:18,400
Yeah.
是的。

91
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:19,400
So like sleep, right?
就像睡觉，对吧？

92
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:20,400
Uh-huh.
嗯哼。

93
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:21,400
Yep.
是的。

94
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:24,840
So if for example, you're going to New York and you're going to visit a friend, you might
所以比如，你要去纽约拜访朋友，你可能会在朋友家借宿。

95
00:03:24,840 --> 00:03:27,240
crash at your friend's house.
在朋友家借宿。

96
00:03:27,240 --> 00:03:28,240
That's right.
没错。

97
00:03:28,240 --> 00:03:29,240
So interesting word.
很有趣的词。

98
00:03:29,240 --> 00:03:31,480
And it is quite commonly used now.
而且现在也很常用。

99
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:35,760
So why don't we hear some examples of how we can use it?
那我们听一些例子，看看怎么用。

100
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:36,760
Example one.
例子一。

101
00:03:36,760 --> 00:03:42,280
Hey man, can I crash at your place tonight?
嘿，老兄，我今晚能在你家借宿吗？

102
00:03:42,280 --> 00:03:43,280
Example two.
例子二。

103
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:45,240
I lost my key.
我丢了钥匙。

104
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:48,480
So I'm crashing at my girlfriend's house.
所以我在女朋友家借宿。

105
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:51,520
Example three.
例子三。

106
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:54,040
No you've been sleeping on my couch for a month.
不，你已经在我沙发上睡了一个月了。

107
00:03:54,040 --> 00:03:57,640
You're not going to crash here tonight.
你今晚不能在这儿借宿。

108
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:58,640
All right.
好的。

109
00:03:58,640 --> 00:03:59,640
Perfect.
完美。

110
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:00,640
So to crash, right?
所以“to crash”，对吧？

111
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:01,920
It's still commonly used today.
现在仍然常用。

112
00:04:01,920 --> 00:04:02,920
Yeah.
是的。

113
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:06,280
Now for the fourth word, groovy.
现在第四个词，“groovy”。

114
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:07,840
Groovy.
很棒。

115
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:09,720
That would be groovy.
那会很棒。

116
00:04:09,720 --> 00:04:13,800
So again, this means like great or cool or really nice.
同样，这意思是很好、很酷或很不错。

117
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:14,800
Yeah.
是的。

118
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:18,160
This is, I think this is one of the main words of the 1960s.
我觉得这是20世纪60年代的主要词汇之一。

119
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:19,160
Everything was groovy.
一切都很棒。

120
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:20,240
Yes, I agree.
是的，我同意。

121
00:04:20,240 --> 00:04:25,440
So it kind of gives you the sense that it's sort of really cool, but in a relaxed way.
它给人一种很酷但很放松的感觉。

122
00:04:25,440 --> 00:04:27,240
Yeah, it's groovy.
是的，很棒。

123
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:28,920
This music is really groovy.
这音乐真的很棒。

124
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:29,920
That's right.
没错。

125
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:34,880
And finally, his friend, he said, hey, I got to split for a while.
最后，他的朋友说：“嘿，我得离开一会儿。”

126
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:35,880
To split.
离开。

127
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:36,880
Okay.
好的。

128
00:04:36,880 --> 00:04:38,840
So if I say I have to split.
所以如果我说“I have to split”。

129
00:04:38,840 --> 00:04:39,840
You have to leave.
你得走了。

130
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:40,840
I have to leave.
我得走了。

131
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:41,840
Yeah.
是的。

132
00:04:41,840 --> 00:04:42,840
Very colloquial.
很口语化。

133
00:04:42,840 --> 00:04:45,000
And it means I have to leave for a little bit.
意思是我得离开一会儿。

134
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:46,000
Yeah.
是的。

135
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Split for a while.
离开一会儿。

136
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,000
That's right.
没错。

137
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
